05281nam a22007455i 9780812205183DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979779115  a97808122051837 a10.9783/97808122051832doi  a(DE-B1597)449501  a(OCoLC)793012718  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a325.3440971 aMelzer, Sara E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aColonizer or Colonized :bThe Hidden Stories of Early Modern French Culture /cSara E. Melzer. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b9 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. France’s Colonial Relation to the Ancient World -- tChapter 1. The Quarrel Between the Ancients and the Moderns as a Colonial Battle -- tChapter 2. The Return of the Submerged Story About France’s Colonized Past in the Quarrel over Imitation -- tPart II. France’s Colonial Relation to the New World -- tChapter 3. Relating the New World Back to France -- tChapter 4. France’s Colonial History -- tPart III Weaving the Two Colonial Stories Together -- tChapter 5. Interweaving the Nation’s Colonial and Cultural Discourses -- tChapter 6. Imitation as a Civilizing Process or as a Voluntary Subjection? -- tChapter 7. Imitation and the “Classical” Path -- tChapter 8. Using the Sauvage as a Lever to Decolonize France from the Ancients -- tConclusion: The Legacy of the Quarrel -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aColonizer or Colonized introduces two colonial stories into the heart of France's literary and cultural history. The first describes elite France's conflicted relationship to the Ancient World. As much as French intellectuals aligned themselves with the Greco-Romans as an "us," they also resented the Ancients as an imperial "them," haunted by the memory that both the Greeks and Romans had colonized their ancestors, the Gauls. This memory put the elite on the defensive—defending against the legacy of this colonized past and the fear that they were the barbarian other. The second story mirrored the first. Just as the Romans had colonized the Gauls, France would colonize the New World, becoming the "New Rome" by creating a "New France." Borrowing the Roman strategy, the French Church and State developed an assimilationist stance towards the Amerindian "barbarian." This policy provided a foundation for what would become the nation's most basic stance towards the other. However, this version of assimilation, unlike its subsequent ones, encouraged the colonized and the colonizer to engage in close forms of contact, such as mixed marriages and communities.This book weaves these two different stories together in a triangulated dynamic. It asks the Ancients to step aside to include the New World other into a larger narrative in which elite France carved out their nation's emerging cultural identity in relation to both the New World and the Ancient World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCivilizationvClassical influences. 0aCivilizationvPhilosophy. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220518340uhttps://www.degruyter.com